  "topic_name": "Force",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "Force is a push or pull that can change the state of motion, direction, or shape of an object. Forces can be contact forces (like friction, muscular force) or non-contact forces (like gravity, magnetic force, electrostatic force). Friction is a force that opposes motion between two surfaces in contact. Friction can be static, sliding, or rolling. While friction causes wear and tear, it is also essential for walking, writing, and braking. Balanced forces result in no change in motion, while unbalanced forces cause acceleration or deceleration.",
    "rules": [
      "Force is a push or pull acting on an object.",
      "Force can change speed, direction, or shape of an object.",
      "Contact forces: friction, muscular force, tension.",
      "Non-contact forces: gravity, magnetic force, electrostatic force.",
      "Friction opposes relative motion between surfaces.",
      "Rolling friction < Sliding friction < Static friction.",
      "Balanced forces cause no change in motion.",
      "Unbalanced forces cause change in motion."
    ]
  },
